The queue 7 test conclusively shows that an HBO FIFO semaphore push leaves
both producer and consumer queries at zero. The vendor offsets and push
encoding match the implementation, so distinguish an HBO-specific failure
from a pBridge-wide SemaHub write failure before attempting descriptors.

Run a bounded 0-1-0 push/pop test on dHub semaphore 25, which Valve assigns
to APB0 data completion and which the probe already configures at depth
one. No dHub descriptor or NAND command uses it during probe-only PIO
operation. Pop only if a token remains.

Clear and sample each test semaphore's write-one-to-clear empty/full
condition latches around PUSH and POP. These snapshots show whether the
command reached the selected SemaHub even when its query counts remain at
zero. Clear the test bits again during cleanup without disturbing unrelated
semaphores.

Generalize the existing consumer-side poll helper so the dHub and HBO tests
use identical query semantics. The existing queue 7 test still runs after
this new discriminator regardless of its result.

